sentences: Jaye Muller (born Jens Müller) is a East German musician and Internet entrepreneur who performed under the name J., and later in a duo named "Muller and Patton" with American musician Ben Patton and under the name "Count Jaye" (since 2015).
In 1992, he released his second solo album, We Are the Majority.
As of 1996, it had sold 350,000 copies worldwide.

Born in East Berlin, Muller (then Müller) left East-Germany for Paris, France in May 1990 after the fall of the Berlin Wall, but prior to German unification.
Born in East Berlin, Muller (then Müller) left East-Germany for Paris, France in May 1990 after the fall of the Berlin Wall, but prior to German unification.
In March 1992, he signed a contract with PolyGram in Paris, France.

Later that year, he used some of the money from this contract to start the weekly newsletter Germany Alert, which chronicled neo-Nazi activity and warned of human rights abuses in Germany at the time.
In 1992, J. was the victim of a home invasion and robbery by three thugs in his apartment.
As of January 1993, the identities of the robbers were still unknown, but J. suspected they were neo-Nazis.
In January 1993, he also released his second solo album, We Are the Majority, in the United States on A&M Records.
It had previously been released in France in October 1992.

In 2015 Muller released a rock album "Bandages Cover The Looting" under the name "Count Jaye & The Hard Beats" co-produced by Müller himself and industry veteran Morris D. Temple.
This was followed up with Count Jaye & The Hard Beats' second release in 2019 named "Hippo Russian Pickle Giant Blue Disguise.
In 2018 Jaye and his wife, singer Michelle Omba, created the live music venue FLASHER FACTORY in the Philippines, for original music only, with great success.
In 2020 the FLASHER FACTORY concept was being expanded into a fully fledged live recording studio located in Lapu Lapu City, Philippines.
